<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="87" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,758,2045]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1119,1145]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[323,545,1119,1145]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[323,545,1119,1145]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a smaller species with a disc diameter less than 
<quantity box="[1100,1178,1119,1145]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cherbonnier, G. &amp; Guille, A." pageId="9" pageNumber="86" refId="ref13891" refString="Cherbonnier, G. &amp; Guille, A. (1978) 48 Echinodermes: Ophiurides. Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, Paris, 272 pp." type="book" year="1978">Cherbonnier &amp; Guille 1978</bibRefCitation>
) and arms about five times the disc diameter long (
<bibRefCitation author="Price, A. R. G." box="[783,909,1155,1181]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="28 - 108" refId="ref17950" refString="Price, A. R. G. (1983) Echinoderms of Saudi Arabia: Echinoderms of the Arabian Gulf Coast of Saudi Arabia. In: Wittmer, W. &amp; Buttiker, W. (Eds.), Fauna of Saudi Arabia. Karger Libri, Basel, pp. 28 - 108." type="book chapter" year="1983">Price 1983</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Price, A. R. G." box="[929,1068,1155,1181]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="28 - 108" refId="ref17950" refString="Price, A. R. G. (1983) Echinoderms of Saudi Arabia: Echinoderms of the Arabian Gulf Coast of Saudi Arabia. In: Wittmer, W. &amp; Buttiker, W. (Eds.), Fauna of Saudi Arabia. Karger Libri, Basel, pp. 28 - 108." type="book chapter" year="1983">Price (1983)</bibRefCitation>
remarked on the extremely variable coloration of this species, and our samples seem to confirm this observation. Live animals collected by the present study are brown, uniform or with lighter spots on the disc and irregular white patches or bands along the arms (
<figureCitation box="[221,373,1262,1289]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1789,1814]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Color morphs of Ophiothrix savignyi [SMNH-178933], Persian Gulf, Bustaneh. A, live photo, dorsal aspect, note the wide red line along the arms and the absence of dark border lines, B–E, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc is grey-blue, the red line is white, B, dorsal aspect, C, ventral aspect, D, dorsal arm, E, disc spines, F, live photo, dorsal aspect, along arms a narrower red line with thin dark borders, G, H, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc has changed to dark blue, the red line has turned white, G, dorsal aspect, H, dorsal arm, I, J, live photos, brown animal with white line along arms, bordered by thin blue lines, I, dorsal aspect, J, ventral aspect, K, L, same animal preserved in ethanol, brown has turned to blue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573476/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 5A, F, G</figureCitation>
). There is a median line along each arm, which may be pale cream (
<figureCitation box="[1133,1220,1262,1289]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1789,1814]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Color morphs of Ophiothrix savignyi [SMNH-178933], Persian Gulf, Bustaneh. A, live photo, dorsal aspect, note the wide red line along the arms and the absence of dark border lines, B–E, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc is grey-blue, the red line is white, B, dorsal aspect, C, ventral aspect, D, dorsal arm, E, disc spines, F, live photo, dorsal aspect, along arms a narrower red line with thin dark borders, G, H, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc has changed to dark blue, the red line has turned white, G, dorsal aspect, H, dorsal arm, I, J, live photos, brown animal with white line along arms, bordered by thin blue lines, I, dorsal aspect, J, ventral aspect, K, L, same animal preserved in ethanol, brown has turned to blue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573476/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 5G</figureCitation>
) or bright red (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1789,1814]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Color morphs of Ophiothrix savignyi [SMNH-178933], Persian Gulf, Bustaneh. A, live photo, dorsal aspect, note the wide red line along the arms and the absence of dark border lines, B–E, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc is grey-blue, the red line is white, B, dorsal aspect, C, ventral aspect, D, dorsal arm, E, disc spines, F, live photo, dorsal aspect, along arms a narrower red line with thin dark borders, G, H, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc has changed to dark blue, the red line has turned white, G, dorsal aspect, H, dorsal arm, I, J, live photos, brown animal with white line along arms, bordered by thin blue lines, I, dorsal aspect, J, ventral aspect, K, L, same animal preserved in ethanol, brown has turned to blue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573476/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 5A, F</figureCitation>
). It is often bordered by two thin dark lines (
<figureCitation box="[727,813,1298,1325]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1789,1814]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Color morphs of Ophiothrix savignyi [SMNH-178933], Persian Gulf, Bustaneh. A, live photo, dorsal aspect, note the wide red line along the arms and the absence of dark border lines, B–E, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc is grey-blue, the red line is white, B, dorsal aspect, C, ventral aspect, D, dorsal arm, E, disc spines, F, live photo, dorsal aspect, along arms a narrower red line with thin dark borders, G, H, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc has changed to dark blue, the red line has turned white, G, dorsal aspect, H, dorsal arm, I, J, live photos, brown animal with white line along arms, bordered by thin blue lines, I, dorsal aspect, J, ventral aspect, K, L, same animal preserved in ethanol, brown has turned to blue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573476/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
) but these may be absent, and then the median red line may be wider (
<figureCitation box="[318,408,1334,1361]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1789,1814]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Color morphs of Ophiothrix savignyi [SMNH-178933], Persian Gulf, Bustaneh. A, live photo, dorsal aspect, note the wide red line along the arms and the absence of dark border lines, B–E, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc is grey-blue, the red line is white, B, dorsal aspect, C, ventral aspect, D, dorsal arm, E, disc spines, F, live photo, dorsal aspect, along arms a narrower red line with thin dark borders, G, H, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc has changed to dark blue, the red line has turned white, G, dorsal aspect, H, dorsal arm, I, J, live photos, brown animal with white line along arms, bordered by thin blue lines, I, dorsal aspect, J, ventral aspect, K, L, same animal preserved in ethanol, brown has turned to blue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573476/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
). In alcohol, the animals turn blue to dark purple and the red line turns white (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1789,1814]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Color morphs of Ophiothrix savignyi [SMNH-178933], Persian Gulf, Bustaneh. A, live photo, dorsal aspect, note the wide red line along the arms and the absence of dark border lines, B–E, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc is grey-blue, the red line is white, B, dorsal aspect, C, ventral aspect, D, dorsal arm, E, disc spines, F, live photo, dorsal aspect, along arms a narrower red line with thin dark borders, G, H, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc has changed to dark blue, the red line has turned white, G, dorsal aspect, H, dorsal arm, I, J, live photos, brown animal with white line along arms, bordered by thin blue lines, I, dorsal aspect, J, ventral aspect, K, L, same animal preserved in ethanol, brown has turned to blue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573476/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 5B, D, G, K, L</figureCitation>
). They have longer (&gt; 
<quantity box="[452,517,1371,1397]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
), rod-like, slightly serrated spines on the dorsal disc and shorter trifid stumps (&lt;
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
) in variable density (
<figureCitation box="[440,529,1406,1433]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1789,1814]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[160,1427,589,1769]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Color morphs of Ophiothrix savignyi [SMNH-178933], Persian Gulf, Bustaneh. A, live photo, dorsal aspect, note the wide red line along the arms and the absence of dark border lines, B–E, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc is grey-blue, the red line is white, B, dorsal aspect, C, ventral aspect, D, dorsal arm, E, disc spines, F, live photo, dorsal aspect, along arms a narrower red line with thin dark borders, G, H, same animal, preserved in ethanol, the brown disc has changed to dark blue, the red line has turned white, G, dorsal aspect, H, dorsal arm, I, J, live photos, brown animal with white line along arms, bordered by thin blue lines, I, dorsal aspect, J, ventral aspect, K, L, same animal preserved in ethanol, brown has turned to blue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573476/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
). The dorsal arm plates are barely wider than long, rhombic and with a median ridge that extends slightly beyond the distal border.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,758,2045]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1437,153,576]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="87" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">
This is the only species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1840" box="[491,614,1479,1505]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,614,1479,1505]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that has so far been reported from the Persian Gulf and Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[1313,1385,1479,1505]" name="Oman" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Oman</collectingCountry>
. It is extremely similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lamarck 1816)" authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1816" baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[381,777,1515,1542]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[381,588,1515,1541]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix ciliaris</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lamarck, J. B." box="[602,770,1515,1542]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" refId="ref15930" refString="Lamarck, J. B. (1816) 2 Histoire naturelle des animaux sans vertebres. L'Imprimerie d'Abel Lanoe, Paris, 568 pp." type="book" year="1816">Lamarck 1816</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, of which 
<bibRefCitation author="Koehler, R." box="[892,1062,1515,1541]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="1 - 486" refId="ref15740" refString="Koehler, R. (1922) Ophiurans of the Philippine Seas and adjacent waters. Smithsonian Institution United States National Museum Bulletin, 100, 1 - 486." type="journal article" year="1922">Koehler (1922)</bibRefCitation>
figured several specimens (under the younger synonym 
<taxonomicName authority="Lyman, 1874" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1874" box="[398,787,1551,1577]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="stelligera">
<emphasis box="[398,633,1551,1577]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix stelligera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lyman, T." box="[639,787,1551,1577]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="221 - 272" refId="ref16407" refString="Lyman, T. (1874) Ophiuridae and Astrophytidae, new and old. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College, Cambridge, 3, 221 - 272. Available from: https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 6705490 (Accessed 12 Dec. 2019)" type="journal article" year="1874">Lyman, 1874</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) with variable color pattern that showed longitudinal lines on the arms as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[346,568,1587,1613]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[346,568,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." box="[582,725,1587,1613]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="1 - 596" refId="ref14516" refString="Clark, H. L. (1938) Echinoderms from Australia. An account of collections made in 1929 and 1932. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, at Harvard College, Cambridge, Mass., 55, 1 - 596, pls. 1 - 28. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 49349" type="journal article" year="1938">Clark (1938)</bibRefCitation>
remarked for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[883,996,1587,1613]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[883,903,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[917,996,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that the median line is always white on the distal arm in animals with red or dark lines. In our specimens, the lines do not change color along the length of the arms. Both species also share a variable disc covering with predominantly trifid stumps, sometimes mixed with long spines (
<bibRefCitation author="Koehler, R." box="[291,448,1695,1721]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="1 - 486" refId="ref15740" refString="Koehler, R. (1922) Ophiurans of the Philippine Seas and adjacent waters. Smithsonian Institution United States National Museum Bulletin, 100, 1 - 486." type="journal article" year="1922">Koehler 1922</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[460,646,1695,1722]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="117 - 131" refId="ref16585" refString="Mortensen, T. (1926) Cambridge Expedition to the Suez Canal in 1924. 6 - Report on the Echinoderms. Transactions of the Zoological Society London, 22, 117 - 131. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1926. tb 00326. x" type="journal article" year="1926">Mortensen 1926</bibRefCitation>
). A distinguishing character may be the shape of the ventral arm plates, which have a strongly concave distal edge in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[682,907,1731,1757]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[682,907,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but are straight in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Clark &amp; Rowe 1971)" authorityName="Clark &amp; Rowe" authorityYear="1971" baseAuthorityName="Clark &amp; Rowe" baseAuthorityYear="1971" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[1132,1152,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1169,1248,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">ciliaris</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E." pageId="9" pageNumber="86" refId="ref14301" refString="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E. (1971) Monograph of Shallow-water Indo-west Pacific Echinoderms. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London, 234 pp." type="book" year="1971">Clark &amp; Rowe 1971</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This is visible in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Clark &amp; Rowe" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[419,532,1767,1793]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[419,439,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[453,532,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on pl. 53, figs 3, 6 and pl. 54, fig. 
<quantity box="[913,955,1767,1793]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" unit="in" value="6.0">6 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Koehler, R." box="[961,1133,1767,1793]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="1 - 486" refId="ref15740" refString="Koehler, R. (1922) Ophiurans of the Philippine Seas and adjacent waters. Smithsonian Institution United States National Museum Bulletin, 100, 1 - 486." type="journal article" year="1922">Koehler (1922)</bibRefCitation>
and in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1214,1436,1767,1793]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[1214,1436,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on pl. VI fig. 
<quantity box="[309,354,1803,1829]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" unit="in" value="6.0">6 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Cherbonnier, G. &amp; Guille, A." box="[362,696,1803,1829]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" refId="ref13891" refString="Cherbonnier, G. &amp; Guille, A. (1978) 48 Echinodermes: Ophiurides. Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, Paris, 272 pp." type="book" year="1978">Cherbonnier &amp; Guille (1978)</bibRefCitation>
, but was not considered an important character by those authors, probably because none of them compared 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Clark &amp; Rowe" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[621,733,1839,1865]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[621,641,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[654,733,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[768,990,1839,1865]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[768,990,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Indeed, we have not been able to find a taxonomic study that compared these two species, despite their striking similarity. In addition, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1213,1436,1875,1901]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[1213,1436,1875,1901]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
usually has minute thorns on the dorsal arm plates (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E." box="[719,948,1911,1937]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" refId="ref14301" refString="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E. (1971) Monograph of Shallow-water Indo-west Pacific Echinoderms. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London, 234 pp." type="book" year="1971">Clark &amp; Rowe 1971</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Guille, A. &amp; Wolff, W. J." box="[959,1193,1911,1937]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="1 - 39" refId="ref15218" refString="Guille, A. &amp; Wolff, W. J. (1984) Resultats biologiques de l'Expedition Snellius Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea I. Zoologische Verhandelingen, 213, 1 - 39." type="journal article" year="1984">Guille &amp; Wolff 1984</bibRefCitation>
), which may however be absent (
<bibRefCitation author="Price, A. R. G." box="[273,400,1947,1973]" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" pagination="28 - 108" refId="ref17950" refString="Price, A. R. G. (1983) Echinoderms of Saudi Arabia: Echinoderms of the Arabian Gulf Coast of Saudi Arabia. In: Wittmer, W. &amp; Buttiker, W. (Eds.), Fauna of Saudi Arabia. Karger Libri, Basel, pp. 28 - 108." type="book chapter" year="1983">Price 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Our specimens lack these thorns but have concave ventral arm plates (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1310,1947,1973]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1957,1982]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,445,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1435,445,1918]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Live photos of Ophiocomella sexradia [SMNH-178932], Persian Gulf, Qeshm Island. A, dorsal aspect, B, ventral aspect, C, dorsal disc, D, oral frame, E, dorsal arm, F, ventral arm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573474" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573474/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Muller, J. H. &amp; Troschel, F. H." pageId="9" pageNumber="86" refId="ref16754" refString="Muller, J. H. &amp; Troschel, F. H. (1842) System der Asteriden. Vieweg &amp; Sohn, Braunschweig, 134 pp." type="book" year="1842">Müller &amp; Troschel (1842)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[455,679,1983,2009]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[455,679,1983,2009]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Müller &amp; Troschel, 1840" authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1840" box="[801,910,1983,2009]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophionyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,910,1983,2009]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Ophionyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) as having keeled, almost rhombic dorsal arm plates and concave ventral arm plates 
<emphasis italics="true" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="87" pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Rückenschilder der Arme gekielt, von fast rhombischer Gestalt. Bauchschilder der Arme breiter als lang, am aboralen Rande ausgeschweift, am adoralen abgerundet.</emphasis>
(p. 117). This description concurs with our specimens. The 
<typeStatus box="[522,570,189,215]" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[695,917,189,215]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[695,917,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was given as 
<collectingCountry box="[1070,1137,189,215]" name="Egypt" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Muller, J. H. &amp; Troschel, F. H." box="[1150,1424,189,215]" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" refId="ref16754" refString="Muller, J. H. &amp; Troschel, F. H. (1842) System der Asteriden. Vieweg &amp; Sohn, Braunschweig, 134 pp." type="book" year="1842">Müller &amp; Troschel 1842</bibRefCitation>
), presumably 
<collectingRegion box="[290,386,225,251]" country="Egypt" name="Al Bahr al Ahmar" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Red Sea</collectingRegion>
, not 
<collectingRegion box="[443,657,225,251]" inferredBySuffix="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Mediterranean Sea</collectingRegion>
, whereas 
<bibRefCitation author="Lamarck, J. B." box="[770,952,225,252]" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" refId="ref15930" refString="Lamarck, J. B. (1816) 2 Histoire naturelle des animaux sans vertebres. L'Imprimerie d'Abel Lanoe, Paris, 568 pp." type="book" year="1816">Lamarck (1816)</bibRefCitation>
referred 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Clark &amp; Rowe" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[1057,1172,225,251]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[1057,1077,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1093,1172,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1209,1315,225,251]" name="Australia" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Australia</collectingCountry>
. Considering the wide geographical distance between both species and the fact that the Indian Ocean specimens have been assigned to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[283,506,297,323]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[283,506,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by all previous authors, we place our specimens in that species. It is obvious that a taxonomic revision is needed and morphological characters alone may not provide a satisfying answer.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,153,576]" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">
<bibRefCitation author="Attaran-Fariman, G. &amp; Beygmoradi, A." box="[199,534,369,396]" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" pagination="1254 - 1261" refId="ref13213" refString="Attaran-Fariman, G. &amp; Beygmoradi, A. (2016) Short communication: The first report of Amphipholis squamata (Delle Chiaje, 1829) (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) from Chabahar Bay - northern Oman Sea. Iranian Journal of Fisheries Sciences, 15, 1254 - 1261." type="journal article" year="2016">
Attaran-Fariman 
<emphasis box="[394,451,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">et al.</emphasis>
(2016)
</bibRefCitation>
reported 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[644,772,369,395]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[644,664,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[679,772,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[977,1045,369,395]" name="Oman" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Oman</collectingCountry>
at Tis port, but the figured animal lacks long disc spines, has few or no disc stumps, dorsal arm plates that are about twice as wide as long and seem to be rugose. All of these characters and its size of about 
<quantity box="[767,847,440,467]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
dd suggest that it is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1861" box="[1080,1437,441,467]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Macrophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="hirsuta" subSpecies="cheneyi">
<emphasis box="[1080,1437,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Macrophiothrix hirsuta cheneyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead. Records of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[381,606,477,503]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="87" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis box="[381,606,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">Ophiothrix savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Andaman and Nicobar Islands by Sadhukhan 
<emphasis box="[1250,1302,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="87">et al</emphasis>
. (2012) are based on a misidentified hexamerous 
